								<!-- Highlight -->
									<section class="box highlight">
										<div class="col-md-6">
                                        <h4>About</h4>
                                        <hr>
                                        <p>WormTraq preprocesses images (see the about page) before identifying and measuring the worms. The default processesing settings
											are configured for certain color settings. However, the lighting or the type of images may vary.
											This page is designed to test your images and figure out the ideal processing parameters for image processing.
                                        </p>
                                        
										</div>
										<div class="col-md-6">
                                        <h4>Instructions</h4>
                                        <hr>
                                        <p>Upload an image. Then fill out the optional processing form. Click "Process Image" when completed.</p>
										</div>
										<div class="col-md-12">
                                        <br>
										<hr>
										<h1>Configure Image</h1>
										<hr>
											<br>
										<form method="post" action="/config" enctype="multipart/form-data"> 
                                        <div class="form-group">
											<div class="col-md-6">
                                            <label><h4>Image File</h4></label>
                                            <hr>
                                            <center><div id="yourBtn" style="height: 50px; width: 150px;border: 1px dashed #BBB; cursor:pointer;" onclick="getFile()">Upload Image</div>
                                            <div style='height: 0px;width: 0px; overflow:hidden;'><input type="file" value="upload" id="upfile" name="photo" accept="image/*" /></div></center>
                                            </div>
											<div class="col-md-6">
												<label><h4>Optional Processing Settings</h4></label>
											<hr>
											<br>
											<br>
                                             <label><h4>Detection Threshold (%)</h4></label>
                                             <br>
                                            <center><input type="text" placeholder=".002" class="form-control" name="area_percent" style="width: 8em"></center>
                                            <br>
										
											<br>
											<label><h4>Contrast (1-100)</h4></label>
											<center><input type="number" class="form-control" name="contrast" value="65" style="width: 8em" /></center>
											<br>
											<label><h4>Hue (1-100)</h4></label>
											<center><input type="number" class="form-control" name="hue" value="100" style="width: 8em"/></center>
											<br>
											<label><h4>Vibrance (1-100)</h4></label>
											<center><input type="number" class="form-control" name="vibrance" value="100" style="width: 8em"/></center>
											<br>
											<label><h4>Noise Removal Cycles (Any positive integer)</h4></label>
											<center><input type="number" class="form-control" name="noise" value="20" style="width: 8em"/></center>
											<br>
											</div>
										</div>
										    <input type="submit" value="Process Image" name="submit">
                                            </form>
                                        <br>
										<h3>Processing Variables</h3>
										<hr>
										<ol>
										   <li><b>1. Detection Threshold: </b>The minimum percentage for which WormTraq will classify an object as a worm. The larger the percentage, the less false positives. The larger, the more potential objects WormTraq will not pick up.</li>
										   <br> <b><li>2. Contrast: </b>How the image is contrasted in order to better seperate light colors from dark colors</li>
											<br> <b><li>3. Hue:</b> Similar effects to contrast.</li>
											 <br><b><li>4. Vibrance:</b> Similar effects to contrast.</li>
											 <br> <b> <li>5. Noise Cycles: </b>WormTraq removes image noise (little dots or isolated dots which appear in the greyscaled image) a certain amount of iterations. The fewer the iterations, the less noise removed, allowing more false positives. The higher the number, the less defined an object like a worm becomes, reducing the chance that it will be correctly identified.</li>

									   </ol>
